The analytical sensitivity of the RT-PCR-Pyroseq assay was assessed using 10-fold serial dilutions of synthetic H7N9 viral RNA transcripts. The results demonstrated that the assay has a detection limit of 100 copies of synthetic RNA for all six codons (Table 2
). The evaluation of the pyrosequencing revealed that the NA-120, NA-294 and NA-276 variants in mixtures (100/0, 90/10, 80/20, 50/50, 20/80, 10/90, 0/100) were detectable from 107 to 102 RNA copies. In this range, the results demonstrated that the detection limit of minor variants was about 20% (20/80 or 80/20) in a mixed population of drug-sensitive and -resistant quasispecies. A cyclic dispensation order (GTCA)10, (GACT)10, and (GTAC)10 was used for detection of NA variants. Fig. 3
showed the representative Pyrosequencing results of 276H/Y, 294R/K, and 120E/V polymorphism in differential mixtures (50/50, 100/0, and 0/100).
